---
import Page from "../layouts/Page.astro";
import { getCollection } from "astro:content";
import fs from "node:fs";
import { formatStamp } from "../lib/format";

let report: any = {};
try {
  report = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync(new URL("../content/sync-report.json", import.meta.url), "utf8"));
} catch {}

const laws = await getCollection("laws");
const cycles = await getCollection("cycles");
const specimens = laws.filter((l) => l.data.specimen).length;
const heldBack: Array<{ statement: string; qed: string }> = report?.held_back ?? [];
const generatedAt: string = report?.generated_at ?? "";
---
<Page title="Colophon — Codex Calculemus">
  <article class="folio">
    <a class="back-link" href="/">← Frontispiece</a>
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-top:var(--space-5)">COLOPHON <span class="sep">·</span> ON THE MAKING</div>
    <h1 class="page-title">Colophon</h1>

    <div class="prose prose--mixed">
      <p>
        <em>Codex Calculemus</em> is a reading-room for the ledger of an autonomous
        theorem daemon, <strong>Leibniz</strong>. The daemon surveys a frontier,
        conjectures, formalizes each claim into Lean, and — where the claim
        survives the cheap gates — asks the kernel to <em>calculate</em> whether it
        holds. This site renders the laws that survived. It is read-only, and it
        rebuilds whenever a new law is published.
      </p>

      <h2>The one rule</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>An LLM may propose; only a mechanical checker may decide.</strong>
        Conjecture and formalization are drafted by language models, but no model's
        opinion ever promotes a law. A proof is admitted only when the
        <strong>Lean kernel</strong> verifies it; faithfulness and refutation are
        settled by <strong>Z3</strong> and a structural corpus, never by a judge.
        The certificate <span class="rubric">Q.E.D.</span> is stamped if and only if
        the kernel verified the proof — it is never hand-set. Everything in
        <a href="/laws">Le Leggi</a> carries one.
      </p>

      <h2>What is gathered here</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>{laws.length}</strong> published {laws.length === 1 ? "law" : "laws"} — <em>Le Leggi</em>{specimens > 0 && <> <span style="color:var(--ink-faint)">({specimens} marked <em>specimen</em> — see below)</span></>}.</li>
        <li><strong>{cycles.length}</strong> circadian {cycles.length === 1 ? "cycle" : "cycles"} of work — <em>Il Lavoro</em>.</li>
      </ul>
      {generatedAt && <p class="colophon-note">Ledger generated: <code>{formatStamp(generatedAt)}</code>.</p>}

      <h2>Promotion is not publication</h2>
      <p>
        When the kernel verifies a law, the daemon <em>promulgates</em> it to the
        Codex. It does not publish it. Publication to this public ledger is a
        separate, deliberate act by a human operator — the daemon can never perform
        it. So a verified law may sit in the Codex, held back, until someone chooses
        to open it.
      </p>
      {heldBack.length > 0 ? (
        <p>
          {heldBack.length} promulgated {heldBack.length === 1 ? "law is" : "laws are"} currently held back, awaiting operator publication:
          {heldBack.map((h, i) => <span>{i > 0 ? "; " : " "}<em>{h.statement}</em></span>)}.
        </p>
      ) : (
        <p>No promulgated laws are currently held back.</p>
      )}

      {specimens > 0 && (
        <>
          <h2>On the specimens</h2>
          <p>
            Some entries are marked <em>specimen</em>. These are <strong>not</strong>
            novel discoveries — they are well-known results, kernel-checked here to
            show the format of a published law while the daemon's discovery frontier
            matures. A specimen is honest about being one; it is never counted as a
            find. The novelty corpus would catch any attempt to pass a textbook
            result off as new.
          </p>
        </>
      )}

      <h2>On the look of the page</h2>
      <p>
        The vellum and ink themes, the illuminated initials, and the typography —
        Instrument Serif for the title hand, Instrument Sans for the body, JetBrains
        Mono for the characteristica — are carried over faithfully from
        <em>Lo Studiolo</em>, the codex surface shared with its sibling,
        <a href="https://codexvitruvianus.com">Codex Vitruvianus</a>. The marginalia
        are austere geometric devices in Leibniz's spirit — the lemniscate, the
        integral <em>ſumma</em>, the dyadic table — drawn in SVG, not photographed.
      </p>
    </div>

    <a class="back-link" href="/">← Return to the frontispiece</a>
  </article>
</Page>
